        <section class="cs-section" id="why">
          <div class="cs-section-label">Why this matters</div>
          <h2 class="cs-h2">As AI shifts from assistant to <em>actor</em>, trust becomes a design problem.</h2>
          <p class="cs-p">
            Traditional software waits for instructions. Agentic systems can plan, decide, and act across multiple steps with less human intervention. That shift changes what users need from an interface.
          </p>
          <p class="cs-p">
            The challenge is no longer just whether an AI response is useful. It is whether people understand <strong>what the system is about to do</strong>, <strong>when to step in</strong>, and <strong>how trust should be repaired when something goes wrong</strong>.
          </p>
          <div class="callout">
            <div class="callout-label">Core idea</div>
            <div class="callout-body">Trust in agentic systems should be dynamic and collaborative, not one-sided. I wanted to explore what that means for the interfaces designers create.</div>
          </div>
        </section>

        <section class="cs-section" id="role">
          <div class="cs-section-label">My role</div>
          <h2 class="cs-h2">An exploratory senior project grounded in <em>real practitioner behavior.</em></h2>
          <p class="cs-p">
            I led this project independently from research question to presentation. My goal was to understand how people already work with AI today, where trust breaks down, and what interface patterns might better support human-agent collaboration in the future.
          </p>

          <div class="meta-row">
            <div class="meta-card">
              <div class="meta-stat">8</div>
