        <section class="cs-section" id="insights">
          <div class="cs-section-label">Insights</div>
          <h2 class="cs-h2">Three themes stood out across the research.</h2>
          <p class="cs-p">
            What people needed was not blind automation. They wanted AI to accelerate work while still preserving accountability, clarity, and room for intervention.
          </p>

          <div class="insight-grid">
            <div class="insight-card">
              <div class="insight-num">Insight 01</div>
              <div class="insight-title">AI is useful for low-risk acceleration, not blind autonomy.</div>
              <div class="insight-copy">Participants described AI as a productivity amplifier. It worked best when helping them move faster, not when taking over end-to-end responsibility without oversight.</div>
            </div>

            <div class="insight-card">
              <div class="insight-num">Insight 02</div>
              <div class="insight-title">People want reasoning, sources, and confidence signals.</div>
              <div class="insight-copy">Trust increased when the system exposed how it arrived at an answer, what information it relied on, and where uncertainty still existed.</div>
            </div>

            <div class="insight-card">
              <div class="insight-num">Insight 03</div>
              <div class="insight-title">Repeated prompting often signals low user confidence.</div>
              <div class="insight-copy">When people keep rephrasing or refining prompts, it often means the system has not interpreted intent well. Most tools treat this as input variation rather than a trust signal.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>

        <section class="cs-section" id="framework">
          <div class="cs-section-label">Framework</div>
          <h2 class="cs-h2">From findings to a <em>bidirectional trust cycle.</em></h2>
          <p class="cs-p">
            Rather than designing for trust as something a human simply grants or withholds, I reframed trust as something that is built between both sides of the interaction. The result was a four-part framework for human-agent teaming.
          </p>

          <div class="framework-grid">
            <div class="framework-card">
              <div class="framework-phase">Phase 1</div>
              <div class="framework-title">Agent Planning</div>
              <div class="framework-copy">Before acting, the agent should clarify assumptions, define task boundaries, and surface ambiguity early. This helps prevent miscalibrated trust before it starts.</div>
              <div class="framework-example">
                <div class="framework-example-label">Example</div>
                <p>“I’m assuming these bold headers represent section titles. Please confirm before I restructure the document.”</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="framework-card">
              <div class="framework-phase">Phase 2</div>
              <div class="framework-title">Agent Proposal</div>
              <div class="framework-copy">Instead of acting invisibly, the system should propose a path with rationale, sources, and confidence. Auditability becomes the foundation for accountability.</div>
              <div class="framework-example">
                <div class="framework-example-label">Example</div>
                <p>“Based on these three sources, I propose this outline. I could not independently verify one claim. Confidence: moderate.”</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="framework-card">
              <div class="framework-phase">Phase 3</div>
              <div class="framework-title">Human Review</div>
              <div class="framework-copy">People need meaningful control, especially for higher-stakes actions. Clear review points, override paths, and visible changes keep authority where it matters most.</div>
              <div class="framework-example">
                <div class="framework-example-label">Example</div>
                <p>Before a report is sent, the system flags low-confidence sections, shows all edits, and requires explicit approval.</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="framework-card">
              <div class="framework-phase">Phase 4</div>
              <div class="framework-title">Mutual Learning</div>
              <div class="framework-copy">Corrections should not disappear after a single interaction. The system should adapt from feedback, while also recognizing when repeated prompting reflects uncertainty or unmet intent.</div>
              <div class="framework-example">
                <div class="framework-example-label">Example</div>
                <p>After repeated rejections of formal copy, the agent learns that the user prefers warmer language and asks about tone earlier next time.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>

