        <section class="cs-section" id="reflection">
          <div class="cs-section-label">Reflection</div>
          <h2 class="cs-h2">This project changed how I think about designing for <em>AI systems.</em></h2>
          <div class="reflection-card">
            <p class="cs-p">
              Before this work, I was already interested in AI as a design space. But researching human-agent teaming pushed me further. It made me think less about single outputs and more about the relationship people build with a system over time.
            </p>
            <p class="cs-p">
              My experience designing AI-powered features at Cisco helped shape this perspective. I kept seeing that the friction was not always about model capability. Often, it was about whether users understood the system well enough to trust it appropriately.
            </p>
            <p class="cs-p" style="margin-bottom:0;">
              That question still feels central to me now: <strong>how do we design AI that feels capable without becoming opaque, and adaptive without becoming overbearing?</strong>
            </p>
          </div>
        </section>

